==Abstract==

This IIP defines Signet, a controlled test network where block production is restricted to holders of a specific signing key. Adapted from BIP 325 for INTcoin's post-quantum Dilithium5 signatures.

==Motivation==

Testnet suffers from unpredictable block production, hashrate instability, and spam. Signet solves these by requiring each block to carry a valid signature from a designated authority, providing a stable and predictable test environment while remaining permissionless to use.

==Specification==

===Consensus Parameters===

Two new fields are added to <code>Consensus::Params</code>:

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Field !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>signet_blocks</code> || bool || Whether this network uses signet block signing
|-
| <code>signet_challenge</code> || bytes || The challenge script that blocks must satisfy
|}

===Challenge Script===

The default INTcoin signet challenge script uses a single Dilithium5 authority key:

<pre>
<authority_pubkey (2592 bytes)> OP_CHECKSIG_DILITHIUM
</pre>

The authority key is derived deterministically:

<pre>
seed = "INTcoin Signet Authority 2026"
seed_hash = SHA3-256(seed)
(sk, pk) = Dilithium5_KeyGen(seed_hash)
challenge = pk || OP_CHECKSIG_DILITHIUM
</pre>

Custom signets can use any valid script via the <code>-signetchallenge</code> CLI option.

===Block Validation===

For signet blocks (when <code>signet_blocks</code> is true), <code>CheckBlock()</code> calls <code>CheckSignetBlockSolution()</code> which:

# Skips validation for the genesis block
# Returns true immediately if the challenge is empty (permissive mode)
# Locates the witness commitment output in the coinbase (identified by <code>0xaa21a9ed</code> magic)
# Extracts the signet solution from the commitment (identified by <code>0xecc7daa2</code> magic)
# Constructs a virtual transaction pair and verifies the solution satisfies the challenge

===Virtual Transaction Pair===

Following BIP 325, validation constructs two virtual transactions:

====To-Spend Transaction====

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Field !! Value
|-
| nVersion || 0
|-
| nLockTime || 0
|-
| Input scriptSig || Block commitment data
|-
| Output scriptPubKey || Challenge script
|-
| Output value || 0
|}

====To-Sign Transaction====

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Field !! Value
|-
| nVersion || 0
|-
| nLockTime || 0
|-
| Input || Spends output 0 of to-spend transaction
|-
| Input scriptSig || Signet solution (signature)
|-
| Output scriptPubKey || OP_RETURN
|-
| Output value || 0
|}

===Block Commitment Data===

The to-spend transaction's scriptSig contains:

<pre>
nVersion (4 bytes) || hashPrevBlock (32 bytes) || modified_merkle_root (32 bytes) || nTime (4 bytes)
</pre>

<code>nBits</code> and <code>nNonce</code> are deliberately excluded so PoW grinding does not invalidate the signature.

The '''modified merkle root''' is computed after stripping the signet solution from the coinbase, avoiding the circular dependency of the signature committing to itself.

===Signet Solution Storage===

The signet solution is appended to the coinbase witness commitment output as additional pushdata:

<pre>
OP_RETURN
  OP_PUSHDATA(36) 0xaa21a9ed <witness_merkle_commitment (32 bytes)>
  OP_PUSHDATA(N)  0xecc7daa2 <signet_solution>
</pre>

The signet header magic bytes are: <code>0xec 0xc7 0xda 0xa2</code>

